article.description: Devin Harris scored 29 points to lead Wisconsin to a 69-57 victory over Ohio State on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Harris sinks five 3s, scores 29 points
article.linkText: Wisconsin wins, stays tied in Big 10 standings
article.story: COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Wisconsin took care of business, one play at a time. Devin Harris made five of seven 3-pointers and scored 29 points to lead Wisconsin (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) to a 69-57 victory over Ohio State on Wednesday night, keeping the Badgers tied for the top spot in the Big Ten. The Badgers (14-3, 5-1) are off to their best start in conference play since the 1962 team won seven of its first eight. They share the lead with Indiana. "I like our guys to do it every possession," said coach Bo Ryan, whose team has won its last three and six of seven. "That's what we talk about -- every possession." Harris' point total was one off his career best against Illinois in the Badgers' last game. He made nine of 12 shots and six of seven free throws in addition to recording four rebounds, four assists and five steals. "I got some good shots early and I was able to knock them down," Harris said. "We've struggled on the road, so this was a big step." Harris said the key to the game was the Badgers' play inside, but his own coach gave him much of the credit for the win. "He dribbled to daylight," Ryan said. "He saw some openings and he did a good job of attacking the rim." Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien went beyond that. "If he's not the best guard in the country, he certainly has to be one of the top few," O'Brien said. Not since coach O'Brien's first Ohio State team in 1997-98 lost its first 14 Big Ten games have the Buckeyes (9-10, 1-5) gotten off to a worse start in the league. Ohio State has lost its last three games and six of seven. After the game, three Ohio State assistant coaches confronted a high school kid who held up a sign that read, "The Wrong Jim O'Brien Resigned." The Boston Celtics' coach, also named Jim O'Brien, quit Tuesday. "He can do what he wants," O'Brien said of the fan. "But I'll tell you what he's not going to do -- he's not going to put the sign right up in my face." J.J. Sullinger scored 14 points for Ohio State, which held a 41-24 upper hand in rebounding yet outscored the Badgers by just six points in the paint. "The guys were looking for us," 7-foot center Velimir Radinovic said. "We just weren't able to hold our men off." Ohio State led 20-18 on Terence Dials' inside shot with 9:17 left in the half, but the Buckeyes didn't hit another basket for almost five minutes. Over that time, the Badgers scored eight of nine points. Both Harris and Clayton Hanson hit 3-pointers and Dave Mader added a 15-foot jumper for a 26-21 lead. Tony Stockman's 3-pointer brought the Buckeyes to 31-27 before the Badgers ran off the final six points of the half. After Zach Morley slashed through the lane for a layup and Harris hit two free throws. In the final seconds of the half, Morley missed a 3-pointer, Harris caught the long rebound and tossed it short of the rim where Boo Wade was waiting to pop it in as the buzzer sounded. "With about a minute and 40 seconds to go in the half, we had a pretty good chance to get it to two points but we botched the end of the first half," O'Brien said. "To be down 10 was a little discouraging." The Badgers then hit five of their first seven shots from the field -- including a layup and a fast-break dunk by Harris -- at the outset of the second half to bump the lead to 49-29. The game never got closer than the final margin, with Ohio State scoring the final seven points of the game. Ryan fought back tears as he spoke about legendary Wisconsin football player Elroy "Crazy Legs" Hirsch, who died earlier in the day at the age of 80. "He's my dad's favorite," Ryan said. "My dad talked about him all the time. It was like the biggest thing in my dad's life when I got this job -- 'Do I get to meet him?' Elroy autographed a jersey for him and a picture. He was a people person, a great guy."
